{"title_page": "I Should Have Known Better", "text_new": "{{short description|Original song written and composed by Lennon-McCartney}}\n{{About|the song by the Beatles}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Should Have Known Better\n| cover      =  Ishouldhaveknownbettersingle.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = US picture sleeve (reverse)\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[the Beatles]]\n| album      = [[A Hard Day's Night (album)|A Hard Day's Night]]\n| A-side     = [[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1964|07|13|df=y}}\n| format     = [[7-inch record]]\n| recorded   = 25\u201326 February 1964\n| studio     = [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI Studios]], London\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 2:44\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| chronology = [[The Beatles]] US\n| prev_title = [[Love Me Do]]\n| prev_year  = 1964\n| next_title = [[And I Love Her]]\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\"'''I Should Have Known Better'''\" is a song by English rock band [[the Beatles]] composed by [[John Lennon]]{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=194}}{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=164}} (credited to [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]), and originally issued on ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)|A Hard Day's Night]]'', their [[soundtrack album|soundtrack]] for the [[A Hard Day's Night (film)|film of the same name]] released on 10 July 1964. \"I Should Have Known Better\" was also issued as the B-side of the US single \"[[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\" released on 13 July. An orchestrated version of the song conducted by [[George Martin]] appears on the North American version of the album, ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)#North American release|A Hard Day's Night Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]''.\n\n==Origin==\n\"I Should Have Known Better\" was one of several songs written and recorded specifically for the Beatles' debut movie, \"A Hard Day's Night\". The harmonica-driven arrangement by the group was similar to that heard on [[Frank Ifield]]'s recording of \"[[The Wayward Wind]]\", a hit on the UK Singles Chart in March 1963. The Beatles were fans of Ifield and his music, and had notably covered his recording of \"[[I Remember You (1941 song)|I Remember You]]\" in their [[Hamburg]] stage act in 1962.\n\n==Recording==\nThe first recording session for the song was on 25 February 1964 at [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI Studios]] when three [[take]]s were attempted, but only one was complete. Take 2 was aborted when Lennon broke into hysterics over his harmonica playing. The song was re-recorded the next day after making some changes to the [[arrangement]].{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=39\u201340}}\n\nLennon's harmonica playing opens the track, the last occasion the Beatles were to feature this instrument on an intro (\"[[I'm a Loser]]\", recorded 14 August 1964 has a harmonica solo) and thus draws a line under a significant period of their early music. The song's middle sixteen section features [[George Harrison]]'s brand new [[Rickenbacker 360/12]] 12-string guitar.{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=109\u2013110}}\n\nThe [[monaural|mono]] and [[stereophonic sound|stereo]] versions have slightly different harmonica introductions. In the stereo version, the harmonica drops out briefly.{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=384}} Also, a noticeably clumsy and audible tape edit is heard during the second chorus between \"You're gonna say you love me too, oh,\" and \"And when I ask you to be mine.\"\n\n==Release==\n\n===United Kingdom===\nIn the UK, \"I Should Have Known Better\" appeared on ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)|A Hard Day's Night]]'' and was released on 10 July 1964. It was not released as a single at that time. In 1976, it was released as a [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] to \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\".{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=592}}{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=200}}\n\n===United States===\nIn the US, \"I Should Have Known Better\" was released on 13 July 1964 as the B-side to \"[[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\"{{sfn|Cross|2005|pp=530\u2013531}}{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=201}} and reached number 53 in the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and number 43 on the ''[[Cash Box]]'' chart.\n\nAs part of the film contract, [[United Artists]] acquired album rights for the American market.{{sfn|Harry|2000|pp=483\u2013484}} The company released a soundtrack album on 26 June 1964 with eight Beatles songs and four instrumentals. \"I Should Have Known Better\" was performed in the film, and it appears on the [[A Hard Day's Night (album)#The American release|soundtrack]]. [[Capitol Records]] released ''[[Something New (Beatles album)|Something New]]'' a month later with songs from the UK version of ''A Hard Day's Night'' that were not used in the film. The songs were also later released by Capitol on the ''[[Hey Jude (album)|Hey Jude]]'' [[compilation album]] in 1970.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988}}\n\n===Continental Europe===\n\"I Should Have Known Better\" was released as a single in a number of continental European countries, including Norway, where it reached number one,{{sfn|MUSIKKEXTRA|2009}} and West Germany, where it reached number six.{{sfn|Inifity Charts|2009}} In Sweden, the song topped the [[Sverigetopplistan|Kv\u00e4llstoppen Chart]] for four weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swedish Charts 1962\u2013March 1966/Kv\u00e4llstoppen \u2013 Listresultaten vecka f\u00f6r vecka > November 1964|url=http://www.hitsallertijden.nl/charts/swedish%20charts/SwedishCharts1962-march66.pdf|publisher=hitsallertijden.nl|language=Swedish|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[John Lennon]] \u2013 [[Doubletracking|double-tracked]] vocal, acoustic rhythm guitar, harmonica\n*[[Paul McCartney]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[George Harrison]] \u2013 twelve-string lead guitar\n*[[Ringo Starr]] \u2013 drums\n:Personnel per [[Ian MacDonald]]{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=109\u2013110}}\n\n==On film==\nThe song is performed in the train compartment scene of ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]''. It was in fact filmed in a van, with crew members rocking the vehicle to simulate the action of a train in motion. [[Paul McCartney]] is seen lip-syncing in the song, both in the train scene and in the live performance at the end of the film, despite not singing in the actual recording.{{sfn|Dowlding|1989|p=68}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{cleanup section|reason=versions may not meet [[:WP:SONGCOVER]].|date=February 2020}}\n*The Naturals covered it in August 1964 on the Beatles record label (Parlophone) and had a minor hit (UK number 24).\n*[[Johnny Rivers]] covered it on his 1964 live album ''[[In Action (Johnny Rivers album)|In Action]]''.\n*[[Jan & Dean]] released the song on their 1965 album ''Command Performance''.\n*[[The Beach Boys]] covered it on their 1965 album ''[[Beach Boys' Party!]]''\n*[[The Skatalites]] recorded an instrumental version under the name \"Independent Anniversary Ska\" in 1966.\n*[[Brinsley Schwarz]] released a cover under the name \"Limelight\" in 1975.\n*[[Stars on 45]] covered it as part of an eight-song Beatles medley in their hit \"[[Stars on 45 (song)|Stars on 45]]\", which reached No. 1 on the US Billboard Hot 100 in June 1981.\n*[[She & Him]] covered the song on their 2008 debut album ''[[Volume One (She & Him album)|Volume One]]'', as a duet with both [[M. Ward]] and [[Zooey Deschanel]] singing.\n*[[The Punkles]] did a punk cover of this song on their first album.\n*[[Phil Ochs]] covered the song with [[Eric Andersen]] during a [[Greenwich Village]] concert in 1964; the live version can be heard on ''[[The Broadside Tapes 1]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nv8vJ3f3AoM|title=Phil Ochs - I Should Have Known Better - Village Gate 1964|date=October 11, 2011|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Ramiele Malubay]] performed the song on the Top 11 week of the seventh season of ''[[American Idol]]''. A studio version of Malubay's performance was released as a single on the [[iTunes Store]] in March 2008.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=22em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n| author=The Beatles\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=The Beatles\n| title=The Beatles Anthology\n| publisher=Cassell& Co\n| location=London\n| isbn=0-304-35605-0\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Cross\n| first=Craig\n| year=2005\n| title=The Beatles: Day-by-Day, Song-by-Song, Record-by-Record\n| publisher=iUniverse, Inc.\n| location=Lincoln, NE\n| isbn=0-595-34663-4\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Dowlding\n| first=William\n| year=1989\n| title=Beatlesongs\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=Inifity Charts\n| year=2009\n| title=German Top 20 - The Chart of 1964\n| url=http://ki.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/~topsi/deu1964/deu_1964t.html\n| accessdate=9 December 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|Inifity Charts|2009}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Harry\n| first=Bill\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=Bill Harry\n| title=The Beatles Encyclopedia: Revised and Updated\n| publisher=Virgin Publishing\n| location=London\n| isbn=0-7535-0481-2\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Lewisohn\n| first=Mark\n| year=1988\n| authorlink=Mark Lewisohn\n| title=The Beatles Recording Sessions\n| publisher=Harmony Books\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-517-57066-1\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=MacDonald\n| first=Ian\n| year=2005\n| authorlink=Ian MacDonald\n| title=Revolution in the Head: The Beatles' Records and the Sixties\n| publisher=Pimlico (Rand)\n| location=London\n| edition=Second Revised\n| isbn=1-84413-828-3\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Miles\n| first=Barry\n| year=1997\n| authorlink=Barry Miles\n| title=Paul McCartney: Many Years From Now\n| publisher=Henry Holt & Company\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-8050-5249-6\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/paulmccartneyman00mile\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Sheff\n| first=David\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=David Sheff\n| title=All We Are Saying: The Last Major Interview with John Lennon and Yoko Ono\n| publisher=St. Martin's Press\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-312-25464-4\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/allwearesayingla00lenn\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=MUSIKKEXTRA\n| year=2009\n| title=Topp 20 Single uke 42, 1964\n| url=http://lista.vg.no/show_list.php?ListsOp=showWeek&week=42&year=1964&listID=1\n| accessdate=9 December 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|MUSIKKEXTRA|2009}}\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|A Hard Day's Night (album)}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|beatles|i-should-have-known-better}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{A Hard Day's Night}}\n{{The Beatles singles}}\n\n[[Category:The Beatles songs]]\n[[Category:The Beach Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n[[Category:Phil Ochs songs]]\n[[Category:She & Him songs]]\n[[Category:Jan and Dean songs]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:1964 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Songs published by Northern Songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Original song written and composed by Lennon-McCartney}}\n{{About|the song by the Beatles}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Should Have Known Better\n| cover      =  Ishouldhaveknownbettersingle.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = US picture sleeve (reverse)\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[the Beatles]]\n| album      = [[A Hard Day's Night (album)|A Hard Day's Night]]\n| A-side     = [[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1964|07|13|df=y}}\n| format     = [[7-inch record]]\n| recorded   = 25\u201326 February 1964\n| studio     = [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI Studios]], London\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 2:44\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]\n| producer   = [[George Martin]]\n| chronology = [[The Beatles]] US\n| prev_title = [[Love Me Do]]\n| prev_year  = 1964\n| next_title = [[And I Love Her]]\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\"'''I Should Have Known Better'''\" is a song by English rock band [[the Beatles]] composed by [[John Lennon]]{{sfn|Sheff|2000|p=194}}{{sfn|Miles|1997|p=164}} (credited to [[Lennon\u2013McCartney]]), and originally issued on ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)|A Hard Day's Night]]'', their [[soundtrack album|soundtrack]] for the [[A Hard Day's Night (film)|film of the same name]] released on 10 July 1964. \"I Should Have Known Better\" was also issued as the B-side of the US single \"[[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\" released on 13 July. An orchestrated version of the song conducted by [[George Martin]] appears on the North American version of the album, ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)#North American release|A Hard Day's Night Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]''.\n\n==Origin==\n\"I Should Have Known Better\" was one of several songs written and recorded specifically for the Beatles' debut movie, \"A Hard Day's Night\". The harmonica-driven arrangement by the group was similar to that heard on [[Frank Ifield]]'s recording of \"[[The Wayward Wind]]\", a hit on the UK Singles Chart in March 1963. The Beatles were fans of Ifield and his music, and had notably covered his recording of \"[[I Remember You (1941 song)|I Remember You]]\" in their [[Hamburg]] stage act in 1962.\n\n==Recording==\nThe first recording session for the song was on 25 February 1964 at [[Abbey Road Studios|EMI Studios]] when three [[take]]s were attempted, but only one was complete. Take 2 was aborted when Lennon broke into hysterics over his harmonica playing. The song was re-recorded the next day after making some changes to the [[arrangement]].{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|pp=39\u201340}}\n\nLennon's harmonica playing opens the track, the last occasion the Beatles were to feature this instrument on an intro (\"[[I'm a Loser]]\", recorded 14 August 1964 has a harmonica solo) and thus draws a line under a significant period of their early music. The song's middle sixteen section features [[George Harrison]]'s brand new [[Rickenbacker 360/12]] 12-string guitar.{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=109\u2013110}}\n\nThe [[monaural|mono]] and [[stereophonic sound|stereo]] versions have slightly different harmonica introductions. In the stereo version, the harmonica drops out briefly.{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=384}} Also, a noticeably clumsy and audible tape edit is heard during the second chorus between \"You're gonna say you love me too, oh,\" and \"And when I ask you to be mine.\"\n\n==Release==\n\n===United Kingdom===\nIn the UK, \"I Should Have Known Better\" appeared on ''[[A Hard Day's Night (album)|A Hard Day's Night]]'' and was released on 10 July 1964. It was not released as a single at that time. In 1976, it was released as a [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] to \"[[Yesterday (Beatles song)|Yesterday]]\".{{sfn|Cross|2005|p=592}}{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=200}}\n\n===United States===\nIn the US, \"I Should Have Known Better\" was released on 13 July 1964 as the B-side to \"[[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\"{{sfn|Cross|2005|pp=530\u2013531}}{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988|p=201}} and reached number 53 in the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and number 43 on the ''[[Cash Box]]'' chart.\n\nAs part of the film contract, [[United Artists]] acquired album rights for the American market.{{sfn|Harry|2000|pp=483\u2013484}} The company released a soundtrack album on 26 June 1964 with eight Beatles songs and four instrumentals. \"I Should Have Known Better\" was performed in the film, and it appears on the [[A Hard Day's Night (album)#The American release|soundtrack]]. [[Capitol Records]] released ''[[Something New (Beatles album)|Something New]]'' a month later with songs from the UK version of ''A Hard Day's Night'' that were not used in the film. The songs were also later released by Capitol on the ''[[Hey Jude (album)|Hey Jude]]'' [[compilation album]] in 1970.{{sfn|Lewisohn|1988}}\n\n===Continental Europe===\n\"I Should Have Known Better\" was released as a single in a number of continental European countries, including Norway, where it reached number one,{{sfn|MUSIKKEXTRA|2009}} and West Germany, where it reached number six.{{sfn|Inifity Charts|2009}} In Sweden, the song topped the [[Sverigetopplistan|Kv\u00e4llstoppen Chart]] for four weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swedish Charts 1962\u2013March 1966/Kv\u00e4llstoppen \u2013 Listresultaten vecka f\u00f6r vecka > November 1964|url=http://www.hitsallertijden.nl/charts/swedish%20charts/SwedishCharts1962-march66.pdf|publisher=hitsallertijden.nl|language=Swedish|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[John Lennon]] \u2013 [[Doubletracking|double-tracked]] vocal, acoustic rhythm guitar, harmonica\n*[[Paul McCartney]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[George Harrison]] \u2013 twelve-string lead guitar\n*[[Ringo Starr]] \u2013 drums\n:Personnel per [[Ian MacDonald]]{{sfn|MacDonald|2005|p=109\u2013110}}\n\n==On film==\nThe song is performed in the train compartment scene of ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]''. It was in fact filmed in a van, with crew members rocking the vehicle to fake the action of a train in motion. [[Paul McCartney]] is seen lip-syncing in the song, both in the train scene and in the live performance at the end of the film, despite not singing in the actual recording.{{sfn|Dowlding|1989|p=68}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{cleanup section|reason=versions may not meet [[:WP:SONGCOVER]].|date=February 2020}}\n*The Naturals covered it in August 1964 on the Beatles record label (Parlophone) and had a minor hit (UK number 24).\n*[[Johnny Rivers]] covered it on his 1964 live album ''[[In Action (Johnny Rivers album)|In Action]]''.\n*[[Jan & Dean]] released the song on their 1965 album ''Command Performance''.\n*[[The Beach Boys]] covered it on their 1965 album ''[[Beach Boys' Party!]]''\n*[[The Skatalites]] recorded an instrumental version under the name \"Independent Anniversary Ska\" in 1966.\n*[[Brinsley Schwarz]] released a cover under the name \"Limelight\" in 1975.\n*[[Stars on 45]] covered it as part of an eight-song Beatles medley in their hit \"[[Stars on 45 (song)|Stars on 45]]\", which reached No. 1 on the US Billboard Hot 100 in June 1981.\n*[[She & Him]] covered the song on their 2008 debut album ''[[Volume One (She & Him album)|Volume One]]'', as a duet with both [[M. Ward]] and [[Zooey Deschanel]] singing.\n*[[The Punkles]] did a punk cover of this song on their first album.\n*[[Phil Ochs]] covered the song with [[Eric Andersen]] during a [[Greenwich Village]] concert in 1964; the live version can be heard on ''[[The Broadside Tapes 1]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nv8vJ3f3AoM|title=Phil Ochs - I Should Have Known Better - Village Gate 1964|date=October 11, 2011|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Ramiele Malubay]] performed the song on the Top 11 week of the seventh season of ''[[American Idol]]''. A studio version of Malubay's performance was released as a single on the [[iTunes Store]] in March 2008.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=22em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n| author=The Beatles\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=The Beatles\n| title=The Beatles Anthology\n| publisher=Cassell& Co\n| location=London\n| isbn=0-304-35605-0\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Cross\n| first=Craig\n| year=2005\n| title=The Beatles: Day-by-Day, Song-by-Song, Record-by-Record\n| publisher=iUniverse, Inc.\n| location=Lincoln, NE\n| isbn=0-595-34663-4\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Dowlding\n| first=William\n| year=1989\n| title=Beatlesongs\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=Inifity Charts\n| year=2009\n| title=German Top 20 - The Chart of 1964\n| url=http://ki.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/~topsi/deu1964/deu_1964t.html\n| accessdate=9 December 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|Inifity Charts|2009}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Harry\n| first=Bill\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=Bill Harry\n| title=The Beatles Encyclopedia: Revised and Updated\n| publisher=Virgin Publishing\n| location=London\n| isbn=0-7535-0481-2\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Lewisohn\n| first=Mark\n| year=1988\n| authorlink=Mark Lewisohn\n| title=The Beatles Recording Sessions\n| publisher=Harmony Books\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-517-57066-1\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=MacDonald\n| first=Ian\n| year=2005\n| authorlink=Ian MacDonald\n| title=Revolution in the Head: The Beatles' Records and the Sixties\n| publisher=Pimlico (Rand)\n| location=London\n| edition=Second Revised\n| isbn=1-84413-828-3\n| ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Miles\n| first=Barry\n| year=1997\n| authorlink=Barry Miles\n| title=Paul McCartney: Many Years From Now\n| publisher=Henry Holt & Company\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-8050-5249-6\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/paulmccartneyman00mile\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last=Sheff\n| first=David\n| year=2000\n| authorlink=David Sheff\n| title=All We Are Saying: The Last Major Interview with John Lennon and Yoko Ono\n| publisher=St. Martin's Press\n| location=New York\n| isbn=0-312-25464-4\n| ref=harv\n| url=https://archive.org/details/allwearesayingla00lenn\n}}\n* {{cite web\n| work=MUSIKKEXTRA\n| year=2009\n| title=Topp 20 Single uke 42, 1964\n| url=http://lista.vg.no/show_list.php?ListsOp=showWeek&week=42&year=1964&listID=1\n| accessdate=9 December 2009\n| ref={{SfnRef|MUSIKKEXTRA|2009}}\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|A Hard Day's Night (album)}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|beatles|i-should-have-known-better}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{A Hard Day's Night}}\n{{The Beatles singles}}\n\n[[Category:The Beatles songs]]\n[[Category:The Beach Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Martin]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:1976 singles