{"title_page": "MARC Train", "text_new": "{{short description|Commuter rail system comprising three lines in the Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox Public transit\n|name = Maryland Area Regional Commuter Rail\n|image =MARC train.svg\n|imagesize = 260 px\n|image2 = MARC 438 (14833026066).jpg\n|imagesize2 = 310px\n|caption2 = A MARC [[Bombardier\u2013Alstom HHP-8|HHP-8]] leads an express train through {{marc|Odenton}}\n|locale = [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area]]\n|owner = [[Maryland Transit Administration]]\n|transit_type = [[Regional rail|Regional]] / [[Commuter rail|commuter]] rail\n|began_operation = {{start date and age|1984}} (as Maryland Rail Commuter)\n|chief_executive = Andrea Farmer\n|lines = 3\n|ridership = 40,100 (Q2 2016)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2016-q2-ridership-APTA.PDF |title=Transit Ridership Report Second Quarter 2016 |date=August 22, 2016 |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |via=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Pages/ridershipreport.aspx |access-date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|annual_ridership = 9,149,900 (2015)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2015-q4-ridership-APTA.pdf |title=Transit Ridership Report Fourth Quarter 2015 |date=March 2, 2016 |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |via=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Pages/ridershipreport.aspx |access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\n|operator = [[Bombardier Transportation]]<br><small>(Camden and Brunswick Lines)</small><br>[[Amtrak]]<br><small>(Penn Line)<br>(under contract to the [[Maryland Transit Administration]])</small>\n|system_length = {{cvt|187|mi}}\n|stations = 42\n|track_gauge = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}} \n|top_speed = {{cvt|125|mph}}\n|marks = MARC\n|host = [[Amtrak]]<br>[[CSX Transportation]]\n|el = [[Amtrak's 25 Hz traction power system|25Hz AC]] on the Penn Line\n|map = [[File:Marctrainmap.svg|310px|MARC oversees the Brunswick Line (orange), Camden Line (green), and Penn Line (purple).]]<br>MARC operates the Brunswick Line (orange), Camden Line (green), and Penn Line (purple).\n|map_state = collapsed\n|website = [https://mta.maryland.gov/marc-train MARC Train official page]\n|alt=|caption=|area served=|line_number=|start=|end=|character=|vehicles=\n}}\n{{MARC Train RDT}}\n\n'''MARC''' ('''Maryland Area Regional Commuter''') Train Service<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mta-d7.cg-devel.com/content/transit-information |title=Transit Information Overview |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=June 24, 2011}}</ref> {{Reporting mark|MARC}}, previously known as '''Maryland Rail Commuter''', is a [[commuter rail]] system comprising three lines in the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area]]. MARC is administered by the [[Maryland Transit Administration]] (MTA), a [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) agency, and is operated under contract by [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier Transportation Services USA Corporation]] (BTS) and [[Amtrak]] over tracks owned by [[CSX Transportation]] (CSXT) and Amtrak.\n\nWith some equipment reaching speeds of {{convert|125|mph}} on the [[Penn Line]], MARC is purported to be the fastest commuter railroad in the United States.<ref name=\"125 mph\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/article/713751/maryland-s-marc-railroad-upgrades-fleet-service-to-bolster-ridership |title=Maryland's MARC Railroad Upgrades Fleet, Service to Bolster Ridership |last=Starcic |first=Janna |date=June 17, 2016 |work=Metro Magazine |access-date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nMARC has three lines, all of which originate and terminate at [[Washington Union Station]]. It operates 94 trains on a typical weekday: the [[Brunswick Line]] (18 trains/19 trains on Fridays),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Routes+Schedules/marc_brunswick-washington.pdf |title=MARC Brunswick Line Timetable |date=March 13, 2017 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> the [[Camden Line]] (21 trains),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Routes+Schedules/marc_camden-washington.pdf |title=MARC Camden Line Timetable |date=March 13, 2017 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Penn Line]] (58 trains).<ref name=\"penn line\">{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Routes+Schedules/marc_penn-washington.pdf |title=MARC Penn Line Full Timetable |date=March 4, 2019 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> The Penn Line is the only line that has weekend service, with 18 trains (comprising 9 round trips) on Saturdays, and 12 trains (comprising 6 round trips) on Sundays.<ref name=\"penn line\" /> Service is suspended or reduced on select Federal holidays.\n\nLike most commuter rail systems in North America, all MARC trains operate in [[Push-pull train|push-pull]] mode, with the [[control car|cab car]] typically leading trains traveling toward Washington. This configuration ensures that diesel locomotive fumes are kept further from the terminal at Union Station, and accommodates elevation gains by placing the locomotive at the head of trains heading outbound from Washington.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n===Brunswick Line===\n{{Main|Brunswick Line}}\nThe '''Brunswick Line''' is a {{cvt|74|mi}} line that runs on [[CSX Transportation|CSX]]-owned tracks between Washington, D.C., and [[Martinsburg station|Martinsburg, West Virginia]], with a {{cvt|14|mi}} branch to [[Frederick station|Frederick, Maryland]]. It is descended from [[Baltimore & Ohio Railroad]] (B&O) service between Washington and its northern and western suburbs.\n\n===Camden Line===\n{{Main|Camden Line}}\nThe '''Camden Line''' is a {{cvt|39|mi}} line that runs on CSX-owned tracks between Washington, D.C., and [[Camden Station]] in [[Baltimore]]. It is descended from B&O commuter routes running between Washington and Baltimore. The B&O began operating over portions of this route in 1830, making it one of the oldest passenger rail lines in the U.S. still in operation.<ref name=\"dilts\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JjrCWPwvHzIC |title=The Great Road: The Building of the Baltimore and Ohio, the Nation's First Railroad, 1828\u20131853 |last=Dilts |first=James D. |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-8047-2629-0 |location=Palo Alto, CA |page=157}}</ref>\n\n===Penn Line===\n{{Main|Penn Line}}\nThe '''Penn Line''' is a {{cvt|77|mi}} line that runs on Amtrak's [[Northeast Corridor]] tracks between Washington, D.C., and [[Perryville station|Perryville, Maryland]], via [[Pennsylvania Station (Baltimore)|Baltimore Penn Station]]. Most trains operate a {{cvt|39|mi}} stretch between Washington and Baltimore, with limited service to [[Martin State Airport station|Martin State Airport]] and Perryville. It is the fastest commuter rail line in North America, with equipment capable of operating at speeds up to {{convert|125|mph}}.<ref name=\"125 mph\" /> Descended from Washington-Baltimore commuter routes operated by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] (hence the name), it is by far the busiest line, carrying more passengers than the other two lines combined. The Penn Line is the only line that operates on weekends.\n\n===Special Western Maryland service===\nTrains have made special weekend trips to and from [[Cumberland station (Maryland)|Cumberland, Maryland]]. Past events have included trains for [[Western Maryland]] residents to attend sporting events in the Baltimore/Washington area, such as [[Baltimore Orioles]] or [[Washington Redskins]] games, or for Baltimore/Washington residents to attend [[Railfest]] in Cumberland and enjoy the scenic mountains and fall foliage of Western Maryland.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Maryland Area Rail Commuter, A Rider's Guide |last=Stakem |first=Patrick H. |publisher=PRB Publishing |year=2008 |asin=B004U7FKQS}}</ref>\n\n===Intermodal connections===\nNearly all stations served by MARC connect with local bus or [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service. Washington Union Station, New Carrollton, College Park, Greenbelt, Silver Spring and Rockville offer connections to the [[Washington Metro|Metrorail]] subway; Baltimore Penn Station and Camden Station both offer connections to the [[Baltimore Light RailLink]]. Additionally, Washington Union Station and Baltimore Penn double as major Amtrak stations, and BWI Airport, Aberdeen, New Carrollton, Rockville, Harpers Ferry and Martinsburg are shared with Amtrak as well. Washington Union Station also offers a connection to the [[Virginia Railway Express|VRE]] network into Northern Virginia.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Point of Rocks MARC 1987.jpg|thumb|left|A MARC [[EMD F9]] leads a service through {{marc|Point of Rocks}} in 1987.]]\n\n===Origins===\nAll three MARC lines date from the 19th century. Service on the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] (B&O) between Baltimore and [[Ellicott City, Maryland|Ellicott City]] began on May 24, 1830; this route included part of what is now the Camden Line.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IEPCqQErPHAC |title=History of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad |last=Stover |first=John F. |date=January 1, 1995 |publisher=Purdue University Press |isbn=9781557530660 |language=en}}</ref> B&O service from Baltimore to Washington, the modern Camden Line route, began on August 25, 1835.<ref name=\"dilts\" />\n\nThe [[Old Main Line Subdivision|B&O's main line]] was extended to Frederick Junction (with a branch to {{marc|Frederick}}) in 1831, to {{marc|Point of Rocks}} in 1832, to {{marc|Brunswick}} and {{marc|Harpers Ferry}} in 1834, and {{marc|Martinsburg}} in 1842. The B&O completed its [[Metropolitan Subdivision|Metropolitan Branch]] in 1873; most service from Martinsburg and Frederick was diverted onto the Metropolitan Branch to Washington and the old main line became a secondary route. This established the basic route for what would become the [[Brunswick Line]].\n\nThe [[Philadelphia, Wilmington and Baltimore Railroad]] (PW&B) completed its line between Baltimore and Philadelphia in December 1838, save for the ferry across the [[Susquehanna River]], which was not bridged until the 1860s. Although the B&O was chartered with the unspoken assumption that no competing line would be built between Baltimore and Washington, the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]-owned [[Baltimore and Potomac Railroad]] (B&P) was completed between the two cities in 1872.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mdot.maryland.gov/Office_of_Planning_and_Capital_Programming/Plans_Programs_Reports/Historical_Documents/Southern_Maryland_Commuter_Service_Technical_Memorandum_07282009.pdf |title=Southern Maryland Commuter Rail Service Feasibility Study |date=August 2009 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration}}</ref> The PW&B was initially hostile to the Pennsylvania (PRR); however, the PRR acquired it in a stock battle with the B&O in 1881. The PW&B soon began operating PRR through service{{snd}}the ancestor of [[Penn Line]] service{{snd}}between Washington and Philadelphia in conjunction with the B&P. Meanwhile, the PRR ended B&O [[Arrangements between railroads|trackage rights]] over the PW&B in 1884, forcing it to open [[Philadelphia Subdivision|its own parallel route]] in 1886. The PW&B and the B&P were combined into the PRR's [[Philadelphia, Baltimore and Washington Railroad]] in 1902.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1902.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1902 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref>\n\nThe B&O ended local service on the [[Frederick Branch (Baltimore and Ohio Railroad)|Frederick Branch]] in November 1949. All B&O passenger service between Baltimore and Philadelphia ended in 1958; local service from Washington was curtailed to [[Camden Station]]. The B&O continued to offer local service to Brunswick plus long-distance service, while the PRR operated a mix of local, intercity, and long-distance service on the [[Northeast Corridor]]. Local service north of Baltimore on the PRR ended around 1964.\n\n===Public takeover===\n[[File:Baltimore & Ohio train 161 from the Beltway, December 1970.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad|B&O]] train near the [[Capital Beltway]] in 1970, running on what is now the [[Camden Line]]]]\n[[File:Penn Central MP54s near Capital Beltway station, July 1970.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]] train near the Beltway in 1970, running on what is now the [[Penn Line]]]]\nIn the mid-20th century, passenger rail service declined owing to a variety of factors{{snd}}particularly the advent of the automobile{{snd}}even while commuting between suburban locations and urban business districts remained common. In 1968, the PRR folded into [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]], which took over its passenger operations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1968.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1968 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> On May 1, 1971, [[Amtrak]] took over most intercity passenger service in the United States, including some trains on the B&O and PRR.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.timetables.org/full.php?group=19710501&item=0008 |title=Nationwide Schedules of Intercity Passenger Service |date=May 1, 1971 |publisher=National Railroad Passenger Corporation (Amtrak) |page=6 |via=The Museum of Railway Timetables}}</ref> The remaining Washington\u2013Baltimore and Washington\u2013Brunswick commuter service was operated by the B&O and Penn Central without subsidies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1971.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1971 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref>\n\nAmtrak initially operated (with federal subsidy) the Washington\u2013[[Parkersburg, West Virginia|Parkersburg]] ''[[West Virginian (Amtrak train)|West Virginian]]'' (later renamed ''Potomac Turbo'' then ''Potomac Special'') The ''Potomac Special'' was cut back to a {{convert|146|mile|adj=on}} commuter-based Washington\u2013Cumberland trip, the ''[[Blue Ridge (train)|Blue Ridge]]'', on May 7, 1973. In early 1974, the B&O threatened to discontinue its remaining unsubsidized commuter services, citing heavy losses. On March 1, 1974, the [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) began a 50% subsidy of the B&O's Washington\u2013Brunswick and Washington\u2013Baltimore service{{snd}}the first state-sponsored commuter rail service to Washington.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1974.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1974 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref><ref name=\"marchistory\">{{Cite web |url=http://mtamaryland.com/about/transitprofiles/MARC_History.cfm |title=History of MARC Train |publisher=Maryland Department of Transportation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117174532/http://mtamaryland.com/about/transitprofiles/MARC_History.cfm |archive-date=January 17, 2010}}</ref> In 1975, the state signed an operating agreement with the B&O, under which the state provided rolling stock and reimbursed the railroad for all operating losses.<ref name=\"marchistory\" /> On October 31, 1976, Amtrak introduced the Washington\u2013Cincinnati ''[[Shenandoah (Amtrak train)|Shenandoah]]'' and cut the ''Blue Ridge'' to a {{convert|73|mile|adj=on}} Washington\u2013Martinsburg trip.<ref name=intercity>{{cite web |title=West Virginia State Rail Plan: Intercity Service Review |author=West Virginia Department of Transportation, State Rail Authority |date=March 12, 2013  |url=http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Intercity_Service_Review.sflb.ashx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006131524/http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Intercity_Service_Review.sflb.ashx |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |pages=4\u20136}}</ref> In the late 1970s, West Virginia began to fund the B&O shuttles between Brunswick and Martinsburg; the shuttles were soon incorporated as extensions of Brunswick service in order to secure [[Federal Transit Administration|Urban Mass Transportation Administration]] subsidies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Maryland_Area_Regional_Commuter_Service.sflb.ashx |title=West Virginia State Rail Plan: Maryland Area Regional Commuter Service |date=March 12, 2013 |publisher=West Virginia Department of Transportation, State Rail Authority |access-date=October 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006071936/http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Maryland_Area_Regional_Commuter_Service.sflb.ashx |archive-date=October 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In December 1981, MDOT purchased 22 ex-PRR coaches for use on B&O lines.<ref name=\"baer1980\" /> The Maryland State Railroad Administration (SRA) was established in 1986 to administer contracts, procure rolling stock, and oversee short line railroads in the state.<ref name=\"marchistory\" />\n\n[[Conrail]] took over the unsubsidized ex-PRR Baltimore\u2013Washington service from Penn Central at its creation on April 1, 1976.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1976.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1976 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> MDOT began subsidizing that service after Conrail threatened to discontinue service on April 1, 1977.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1977.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1977 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> Prior to 1978, most ex-PRR Baltimore\u2013Washington service was operated by aging [[PRR MP54|MP54]] [[electric multiple unit]]s, most dating back to the line's 1933 electrification. In 1978, Amtrak and the City of Baltimore negotiated with the [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] to lease a number of new [[Arrow (railcar)|Arrow]] railcars to replace the MP54s.<ref name=\"baer1978\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1977.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1977 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> With funding from Pennsylvania and Maryland, Amtrak used some of the cars to initiate a Philadelphia\u2013Washington commuter trip, the ''[[Chesapeake (train)|Chesapeake]]'', on April 30, 1978.<ref name=\"baer1978\" /> The ''Chesapeake'' stopped at some local stations but fewer than the Conrail service; it provided commuter service from north of Baltimore for the first time since the 1960s.\n\n[[BWI Rail Station]] opened for Amtrak and Conrail trains on October 26, 1980.<ref>{{Cite news |title=BWI Airport Rail Link Celebrates Opening |last=Shifrin |first=Carole |date=October 24, 1980 |work=The Washington Post |page=D3 |id = {{ProQuest|147198286}}}}</ref> In August 1982, Conrail trains began stopping at [[Capital Beltway station]], used by intercity trains since 1970. {{marc|Lanham}} and {{marc|Landover}} stations were closed.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Commuter Trains' New Stop: Beltway Station |date=August 11, 1982 |work=The Washington Post |page=MD11 |id = {{ProQuest|147456718}}}}</ref> Two additional round trips{{snd}}one in the peak direction, and one reverse for commuters working in Baltimore{{snd}}were added on July 5, 1983.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Baltimore-D.C. Commuter Train Trips to Increase |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=June 9, 1983 |work=The Washington Post |page=B8 |id = {{ProQuest|147548056}}}}</ref> On October 30, 1983, Amtrak and MARC moved from Capital Beltway into a new platform and waiting room at nearby [[New Carrollton station]], served by Metro since 1978.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Fuchs |first=Tom |date=April 2009 |title=30th Anniversary of New Carrollton Station |url=http://www.actfortransit.org/archives/publications/TransitTimes-V23-2-Apr2009.pdf |journal=Transit Times |volume=23 |issue=2 |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Metro Parking Spots Rented to Amtrak For Temporary Use at New Carrollton |date=October 28, 1983 |work=The Washington Post |page=C12 |id = {{ProQuest|147479061}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://history.amtrak.com/archives/i-new-i-new-carrollton-station-brochure-1983 |title=New New Carrollton station |date=1983 |publisher=Amtrak}}</ref> The [[West Baltimore station#History|Edmondson Avenue]] and Frederick Road stops in Baltimore were replaced by [[West Baltimore station]] on April 30, 1984.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18762237/marc_west_baltimore/ |title=New station, schedule for rail users |last=McCord |first=Joel |date=April 28, 1984 |work=Baltimore Sun |via=Newspapers.com}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, MDOT began installing highway signs to point drivers to commuter rail stations.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bulletin Board |date=May 28, 1981 |work=The Washington Post |page=MD9 |id = {{ProQuest|147307755}}}}</ref> In 1982, law changes allowed Conrail to shed its commuter rail operations in order to focus on its more profitable freight operations. On January 1, 1983, public operators (including [[Metro-North Railroad]], [[NJ Transit]], and [[SEPTA Regional Rail]]) took over Conrail commuter rail systems in the Northeast. MDOT began paying Amtrak to run the ex-PRR Washington\u2013Baltimore service.<ref name=\"marchistory\" /><ref name=\"baer1980\" /> That service was branded as AMDOT (Amtrak Maryland Department of Transportation).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1983/07/11/many-commute-from-baltimore-to-district-jobs/3842d475-8495-411f-af33-6d7a2be73453/ |title=Many Commute From Baltimore To District Jobs |last=Sargent |first=Edward D. |date=July 11, 1983 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> On October 1983, with low patronage and largely duplicated by the MDOT-subsidized service, the ''Chesapeake'' was discontinued. In 1984, the SRA renamed its three subsidized lines as ''MARC'' as a branding strategy. Operations remained the same, but public-facing elements like schedules and crew uniforms were consolidated under the new name.<ref name=\"marchistory\" /><ref name=\"baer1980\" /> MARC soon began calling its three lines the [[Penn Line]], [[Camden Line]], and [[Brunswick Line]].\n\n===Improved service===\n[[File:MARC 64 Jessup MD June 94 - Flickr - drewj1946.jpg|thumb|right|MARC train led by an [[EMD E9]] (former [[Burlington Northern]]) at Jessup in 1994]]\nIn October 1986, MARC began testing an Amtrak [[EMD AEM-7|AEM-7]] locomotive, looking to use push-pull trains to replace the Arrows.<ref name=\"baer1980\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1980.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1980\u201389 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> On February 27, 1989, MARC increased Washington\u2013Baltimore service from 7 to 13 weekday round trips. A new park-and-ride station opened at {{marc|Bowie State}} (site of Jericho Park station, closed in 1981) and [[Bowie Railroad Buildings|Bowie station]] was closed.<ref name=\"baer1980\" /> Two more round trips were added in May 1989.<ref name=\"baer1980\" />\n\nOn May 1, 1991, MARC service was extended north from Baltimore to {{marc|Perryville}} with intermediate stops at {{marc|Martin State Airport}}, {{marc|Edgewood}}, and {{marc|Aberdeen}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-05-01/news/1991121140_1_perryville-commuter-rail-service-marc |title=Commuter rail, Perryville to Baltimore, starts today: MARC line's new Susquehanna Flyer out to attract commuters. ALL ABOARD! |last=Reid |first=Bruce |date=May 1, 1991 |work=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> Between 1988 and 1993, MARC expanded service from 34 to 70 total daily trips across the system.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1993-07-24/news/1993205036_1_buckley-marc-system-camden-station |title=MARC plans to raise fares 19 percent boost to be proposed |last=Lee |first=Edward |date=July 24, 1993 |work=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> In 1995, 800 parking spaces were added to [[Odenton station]].<ref name=\"parking1995\" />\n\nFrom 1989 to 1996, the Camden Line had high ridership growth and substantial changes to its stations. A new station at {{marc|Savage}} just off [[Maryland Route 32|Route 32]] was opened on July 31, 1989.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Columbia Commuters Get a Station Break: Convenience Touted at New MARC Stop in Savage Station Opens in Savage |last=Worden |first=Amy |date=August 3, 1989 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|139977789}}}}</ref> MARC began service to [[Greenbelt station]] in May 1993, seven months before Metro began serving the station.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1993/12/10/lukewarm-thrill-at-end-of-line/017c98b2-5d12-4e61-ad31-2e89e54109e6/ |title=LUKEWARM THRILL AT END OF LINE |last=Meyer |first=Eugene L. |date=December 10, 1993 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On January 31, 1994, MARC expanded midday service on the Camden and Brunswick lines, opened [[Laurel Race Track station]] to relieve a parking shortage at [[Laurel station (MARC)|Laurel station]], and closed the underused Berwyn station on the Camden Line.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-01-18/news/1994018046_1_marc-midday-service-union-station |title=MARC is off to the races Jan. 31 |last=Jensen |first=Peter |date=January 18, 1994 |newspaper=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> On December 12, 1994, [[Muirkirk station (MARC)|Muirkirk station]] (originally planned as South Laurel) was opened to reduce congestion on nearby [[U.S. Route 1 in Maryland|Route 1]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Commuter Lines Add Stations in Va. and Md. |last=Fehr |first=Stephen |date=December 12, 1994 |work=The Washington Post |page=D3 |id = {{ProQuest|757194485}}}}</ref> In 1996, a $1.2 million project added 600 parking spaces at Savage station to relieve crowding.<ref name=\"parking1995\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-06-22/news/1995173023_1_commuters-marc-stations-parking-lots |title=600 spaces to be added to MARC station parking lot by spring |last=Hedgpeth |first=Dana |date=June 22, 1995 |work=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> In July 1996, the Elkridge station was closed and replaced with [[Dorsey station]], which has a larger parking area and a dedicated interchange with [[Maryland Route 100|Route 100]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-56834962.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911025205/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-56834962.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 11, 2016 |title=State DOT Considers New Road near Dulles |last=Spellmann |first=Karyn |date=July 8, 1996 |work=The Washington Times |url-access=subscription  |via=Highbeam Research}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baltometro.org/reports/MajorTransMilestones.pdf |title=MAJOR TRANSPORTATION MILESTONES IN THE BALTIMORE REGION SINCE 1940 |last=Logan |first=Mary |date=December 1, 2005 |publisher=Baltimore Metropolitan Council |page=12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227234104/http://www.baltometro.org/reports/MajorTransMilestones.pdf |archive-date=December 27, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 1987, the B&O was merged into [[CSX Transportation|CSX]]. CSX continued to operate Camden and Brunswick Line service.<ref name=\"baer1980\" /> On July 6, 1987, MARC opened [[Metropolitan Grove station]] \u2013 the first new station on the Brunswick line in over a century.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=Summer 1987 |title=News and Upcoming Events |url=http://actfortransit.org/archives/publications/TransitTimes-V01-2-Sum1987.pdf |journal=Transit Times |publisher=Action Committee for Transit |volume=1 |issue=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Md. Commuters Get Another Way to Go |date=July 9, 1987 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|139235759}}}}</ref>\n\n===Keolis controversy===\nBeginning as early as June 2010, MARC began looking for a new operator to replace [[CSX Transportation]] for the [[Camden Line|Camden]] and [[Brunswick Line|Brunswick]] Lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trn.trains.com/news/news-wire/2010/06/marc-to-seek-new-operator-for-csx-run-routes|title=MARC to seek new operator for CSX-run routes|publisher=Trains Magazine|date=14 June 2010|accessdate=14 June 2010 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nControversy first arose when the French-owned and [[Montgomery County, Maryland]]-based [[Keolis]] (already operating [[Virginia Railway Express]] trains) was the only bidder for the contract. The bidding process was suspended in the fall of 2010 due to lack of competition. Before bidding reopened in 2011, Maryland passed a law (at the request of Leo Bretholz and other [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivors) requiring Keolis's majority owner, French state railway company [[SNCF]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/06/AR2010070605169_2.html?sid=ST2010070605786 |title=Holocaust group faults VRE contract |last=Shaver |first=Katherine |date=July 7, 2010 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> to fully disclose its role in transporting Jews to concentration camps during [[World War II]] (while SNCF was under control of the Nazi government). This disclosure would need to meet the satisfaction of the Maryland state archivist before Keolis would be allowed to place a bid for MARC service. Keolis faced similar issues while bidding for VRE operations in 2009, but was eventually given that contract.\n\nKeolis and SNCF lawyers claimed that all documentation required by the law had been produced long before.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wbaltv.com/politics/27069604/detail.html |title=No way to run a railroad |date=March 3, 2011 |publisher=WBAL TV |access-date=September 1, 2012}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This was also asserted by Don Phillips in the July 2011 issue of ''[[Trains (magazine)|Trains Magazine]]''. Phillips states that a full 914-page independent report and complete history of SNCF's role in the Holocaust, released in 1996, is currently being translated into English.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Phillips |first=Don |date=July 2011 |title=Lawsuits, Commuter Trains and the Holocaust |magazine=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]] |page=11}}</ref> Phillips cites from the publicly available English introduction to the report, noting that while some SNCF workers worked with the Nazis, acts of sabotage were frequent, and the Nazis shot 819 SNCF workers for refusing to carry out the rail orders of the government. An additional 1200 railway workers were themselves sent to concentration camps over SNCF rails. Phillips also notes that SNCF does business with the [[Israel Railways|Israel rail system]] and works without government prompting to educate the current generation about the war and Holocaust.\n\nIn June 2011, the future of Keolis's ability to bid on the MARC contract remained up in the air with the new disclosure law in place. No other bidder had emerged to replace CSXT. On June 5, 2011, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' ran an editorial critical of the disclosure law. The Post claimed that SNCF has been working for years on digitizing its records, and the Maryland law may require items or formats counter to SNCF's current system and/or French law. The article also stated that some in the Maryland Attorney General's Office worried the law was not Constitutional, may risk retaliation towards Maryland firms overseas, and may risk federal funding for Maryland \"by imposing arbitrary procurement demands on a single company.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/no-way-to-run-a-railroad/2011/06/03/AGk2gmJH_story.html |title=No way to run a railroad |last=Lind |first=Michael |date=June 5, 2011 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.jewishtimes.com/index.php/jewishtimes/news/jt/local_news/state_archivist_sncf_archives_might_not_be_enough/29884 |title=State archivist SNCF archives might not be enough |last=Rubin |first=Neil |date=February 10, 2012 |work=Baltimore Jewish Times}}</ref>\n\nMTA issued a new Request for Proposals for the operations and maintenance of MARC services on the Brunswick and Camden Lines on July 14, 2011, with a deadline for proposals on November 21, 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.masstransitmag.com/news/10454236/md-mta-keolis-mum-on-bids-to-run-marc-lines |title=MD MTA Keolis mum on bids to run MARC lines |last=Sohr |first=Nicholas |date=November 21, 2011 |work=The Daily Record via masstransitmag.com}}</ref> On October 17, 2012, a $204 million contract to run the Camden and Brunswick lines was awarded to the [[Canada|Canadian]] company [[Bombardier Transportation]],<ref name=\"Weir\">{{Cite news |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/bombardier-wins-204m-marc-commuter-train-contract/article/2511058#.UI1WIWe_Msc |title=Bombardier wins $204m MARC commuter train contract |last=Weir |first=Kytja |date=October 17, 2012 |work=[[The Washington Examiner]] |access-date=October 28, 2012}}</ref> effectively ending the Keolis controversy. The pre-service transition period began on the Thursday of that week, during which time CSXT continued to operate MARC trains.<ref name=\"Weir\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/dr-gridlock/wp/2012/10/17/new-company-to-operate-some-marc-trains/ |title=New company to operate some MARC trains |last=Shaver |first=Katherine |date=October 17, 2012 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=December 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Rolling stock==\n{{As of|2018}}, MARC operates with the following equipment:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedieselshop.us/MARC.HTML|title=Maryland Rail Commuter Roster|website=www.thedieselshop.us|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Locomotives ===\n====Current====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Image || Manufacturer || Model || Quantity || Unit Numbers || Notes\n|-\n| [[File:MARC GP39PH-2 70.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD GP40-based passenger locomotives#GP39H-2|GP39H-2]] || 6 || 70\u201375 || Entered service in 1992.\n|-\n| [[File:MARC 4911 (14669332360).jpg|150px]]\n| [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier\u2013]] [[Alstom]] || [[Bombardier\u2013Alstom HHP-8|HHP-8]] || 6 || 4910\u20134915 ||\nOnly electric locomotives in fleet, first entered service in 1998. All units underwent refurbishment in 2017\u20132018.<ref name=\"marc-advisory-council-september-2017\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.mta.maryland.gov/ckfinder/userfiles/files/MARCRAC_Minutes_2017-09-21.pdf |title=MARC Riders Advisory Council Meeting Minutes |date=September 21, 2017 |website=MTA Maryland |accessdate=June 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:MARC 29 (9116980755).jpg|150px]]\n| [[MPI MPXpress|MPI]] || [[MPI MPXpress#MP36PH-3C|MP36PH-3C]] || 26 || 10\u201335 ||\nReplaced GP40WH-2s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtamaryland.com/services/marc/serviceInformation/On_Your_MARC_Text.cfm |title=MTA Expands MARC Penn Line Service |publisher=MTA Maryland Service Information |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331152834/http://www.mtamaryland.com/services/marc/serviceInformation/On_Your_MARC_Text.cfm |archivedate=March 31, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Entered service December 2009.\n|-\n|[[File:MARC Charger Testing in Odenton.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Siemens]] || [[Siemens Charger|SC-44]] || 8<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Board Of Public Works Approves $58 Million Contract For Eight MARC Locomotives |date=September 17, 2015 |publisher=[[Maryland Transit Administration]] |location=Baltimore, Maryland |url=http://mta.maryland.gov/board-public-works-approves-58-million-contract-eight-marc-locomotives |access-date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> || 80\u201387 ||Delivered December 2017 \u2013 April 2018<ref name=\"jan 2018 minutes\">{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Community/MARCRAC_Minutes_20178-01-18.pdf |title=MARC Riders Advisory Council Meeting Summary Minutes |website=MTA Maryland |date=January 18, 2018 |access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mta.maryland.gov/content/penn-line-schedule-change-april-23 |title=Penn Line schedule change: April 23 |website=MTA Maryland |access-date=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Former====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Image || Manufacturer || Model || Quantity || Unit Numbers || Notes\n|-\n| [[File:EMD AEM-7 MARC 4902 at Union Station.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]]/[[ASEA]] || [[EMD AEM-7|AEM-7]] || 4 || 4900\u20134903 ||\nRetired as of April 2017, units were placed in storage,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mta-d7.cg-devel.com/sites/default/files/MARCRAC_Minutes_2017-04-20.pdf |title=MARC Riders Advisory Council Meeting Minutes |date=April 20, 2017 |website=MTA Maryland |access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref> pending disposition.\n|-\n| [[File:MARC52.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD GP40-based passenger locomotives#GP40WH-2|GP40WH-2]] || 19 || 51\u201369 || \nReplaced by MP36PH-3Cs. Units 67\u201369 were rebuilt from [[EMD GP40|GP40]] work locomotives 30\u201332. One unit, no. 68, remains for non-revenue work duty and rescue use only. Several units rebuilt into MPI MP32PH-Q for Central Florida's [[SunRail]] commuter train. \n|-\n| [[File:MARC 64 Jessup MD June 1994xRP - Flickr - drewj1946.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD E9|E9AM]] || 10 || 60\u201369 ||Ex-[[Burlington Northern Railroad]]. Units were originally built as [[EMD E8|E8As]]. 67\u201368 renumbered to 91\u201392.\n|-\n| [[File:MARC 83 at Brunswick MD June 1994xRP - Flickr - drewj1946.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD F9|F9PH]] || 5 || 81\u201385 ||Ex-[[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]]. Units were rebuilt by [[Morrison-Knudsen]] from former [[EMD F7|F7]] locomotives.  Former MDOT 7181\u20137185.\n|-\n| [[File:MARC No. 7100 (15519101509).jpg|150px]] || [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD F7|F7 APCU]] ||1 || 7100 || Ex-Baltimore & Ohio Railroad F7 #4553, converted into an NPCU. In the early 2000s, this unpowered unit occasionally substituted for a cab car. In addition to serving as an all-purpose control unit, it also had a head-end power generator that supplied electricity to the train. 7100 is now preserved at the B&O Railroad Museum and is used in push pull service on the Baltimore and Ohio museum railroad tour.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.trainweb.org/csxrailfan/nov99/marc7100/marc7100.html |title=The MARC 7100 Returns! (November 1999 ''CSX Railfan Magazine'') |website=TrainWeb |access-date=September 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>http://www.borail.org/7100.aspx</ref>\n|}\n\n===Passenger cars===\n====Current====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Image\n! Manufacturer\n! Model\n! style=\"width:250px\" colspan=2 | Quantity\n! style=\"width:75px\" | Delivered\n! style=\"width:70px\" | Car Numbers\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | [[File:MARC deadhead (12373901765).jpg|150px]]\n| rowspan=2 | [[Sumitomo Corporation|Sumitomo]]/ [[Nippon Sharyo]]\n| rowspan=2 | MARC II\n| rowspan=2 | 60\n|\nMARC IIA\n*16 coaches\n*11 cab cars\n| 1985\u20131987\n| Coaches: 7700\u20137715<br />\nCabs: 7745\u20137756\n|\n*Single level cars.\n*7709 and 7752 were destroyed in 1996 Silver Spring train collision.\n*7711\u201314 were converted to \"Bike Cars\", equipped with 16 bike racks, left side, and 22 passenger seats on the right.\n*The remaining cars were retired in 2015 after being replaced by Bombardier Multilevel cars and have been placed in storage.\n|- \n|\nMARC IIB\n*28 coaches\n*6 cab cars\n| 1991\u20131993\n| Coaches: 7716\u20137735, 7791\u20137799<be/>\nCabs:7757\u20137762\n|\n*Single level cars.\n*All units overhauled in 2009\u20132011 by [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]].\n*7720 was destroyed in the [[1996 Maryland train collision|1996 Silver Spring train collision]].\n|-\n| [[File:MARC 537 (12374362454).jpg|150px]]\n| [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries Rolling Stock Company|Kawasaki]] \n| MARC III\n| 63\n|\n*49 coaches \n*14 cab cars\n| 1999\u20132001\n| Coaches:\n7800\u20137834<br />7845\u20137858\n\nCabs:<br />7870\u20137876<br />7890\u20137896\n|\n*[[Bilevel rail car|Bilevel]] cars.\n*All units undergoing overhauls by Bombardier; delivery of first overhauled units expected Q2 2018, continuing through 2020.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=MARC Train Awards $36.8 Million Contract to Bombardier Transportation to Overhaul 63 Bi-Level Rail Cars |date=February 4, 2016 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |location=Baltimore, MD |url=https://www.mta-d7.cg-devel.com/marc-train-awards-368-million-contract-bombardier-transportation-overhaul-63-bi-level-rail-cars}}</ref><ref name=\"jan 2018 minutes\" />\n*7826\u20137834 and 7855\u20137858 are ex-[[Virginia Railway Express|VRE]] cars purchased used in 2008. They were first purchased by VRE in 2000 using an option for MARC's original MARC III order.<ref>{{Cite news |title=New cars may ease MARC crowding |last=Michael Dresser |date=August 20, 2008 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |pages=1B, 6B}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:MARC 8046.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]] \n| MARC IV\n| 54\n|\n*39 coaches\n*15 cab cars\n| 2014\n| Coaches: \n8000\u20138038 Cabs:\n\n8039\u20138054 \n|\n*Bilevel cars marketed by Bombardier as \"[[Bombardier MultiLevel Coach|MultiLevels]]\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mta-d7.cg-devel.com/governor-o%E2%80%99malley-announces-marc-purchase-54-multi-level-passenger-cars |title=Governor O'Malley Announces Marc to Purchase 54 Multi-level Passenger Cars |date=November 2, 2011 |publisher=MTA Maryland |access-date=September 1, 2012}}</ref>\n*Delivery in June/July 2014.\n*Coaches entered service 2014-early 2015; first cab cars accepted for passenger service September 2016.\n|}\n\n====Former====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Image\n! Manufacturer \n! Model\n! style=\"width:250px\" colspan=2 | Quantity\n! style=\"width:75px\" | Delivered\n! style=\"width:70px\" | Car Numbers\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[File:MARC 20 at Gaithwersburg, MD on August 14, 1987 (22763179726).jpg|150px]]\n| [[Budd Company|Budd]] \n| [[Budd Rail Diesel Car|RDC]]\n| 16\n| Self propelled cars\n| 1984 (inherited at inception)\n| 1, 3, 8, 9, 11, 12, 20, 22, 23, 800, 9801, 9802, 9805, 9918, 9921, 9941\n|Inherited from various railroads\n|-\n|[[File:Single level passenger car in Hyannis.JPG|150px]]\n|[[Budd Company|Budd]] \n| MARC I\n| 22\n| Single level cars\n| 1984 (inherited at inception)\n| 100\u2013114, 130\u2013134, \n140\u2013149, 150\u2013154,\n\n160\u2013169,\n\n190\u2013191<ref>Amtrak Employee Timetable, 1990</ref>\n| Ex-[[Pennsylvania Railroad]], [[Norfolk and Western Railway]], [[NJ Transit Rail Operations|NJ Transit,]] and [[SEMTA Commuter Rail|SEMTA]]. Some operate at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad museum.\n|-\n| [[File:Gallery Cars (4782645545).jpg|150px]]\n| [[Pullman Company|Pullman Standard]] \n| Gallery cars\n| 12\n| Bi-level coaches\n| 2004\n| 7900\u20137911\n| Ex-[[Metra]] gallery cars. Replaced by Bombardier MARC IV.\n|-\n|}\n\n==Incidents==\n\n===1996===\n{{main|1996 Maryland train collision}}\n[[File:Brunswick train crash memorial front.jpg|left|thumb|150px|MARC Memorial in the grounds of the Brunswick train station.]]\n\nOn February 16, 1996, during the Friday evening [[rush hour]], an eastbound train headed to [[Washington Union Station]] via the Brunswick Line [[1996 Maryland train collision|collided]] with the westbound [[Amtrak]] ''[[Capitol Limited (Amtrak train)|Capitol Limited]]'' headed to [[Chicago]] via [[Pittsburgh]]. The collision occurred at Georgetown Junction on a snow-swept stretch of track just west of [[Silver Spring, Maryland]]. The crash left 11 people dead aboard the MARC train. Three died of injuries suffered in the impact alone, with the rest succumbing to the ensuing smoke and flames or a combination of the two. Engineer Ricky Orr and conductors Jimmy Major Jr. and Jim Quillen were among the victims. Eight Jobs Corps students also were killed during the accident.\n\nThe NTSB report concluded that the MARC crew apparently forgot the approach signal [[Railway signal#Aspects and indications|aspect]] of the Kensington [[Railway signal#Colour-position signals|color-position signal]] after making a [[Request stop|flag stop]] at [[Kensington station (Maryland)|Kensington station]]. The MARC train was operating in [[Push-pull train|push]] mode with the cab control car out front. The Amtrak locomotives were in the crossover at the time of the collision; the MARC cab control car collided with the lead Amtrak unit, [[EMD F40PH|F40PH]] #255, rupturing its fuel tank and igniting the fire that caused most of the casualties. The second unit was a [[GE Genesis#P40DC|GE Genesis P40DC]] #811, a newer unit that has a fuel tank that is shielded in the center of the frame. The official investigation also suggests that the accident might have been prevented if a [[human reliability|human-factors analysis]] had been conducted when modifications to the track signaling system were made in 1992 with the closing of nearby QN tower.\n\n===2008===\nOn February 7, 2008, a train derailed at Union Station after it was hit by an Amtrak [[switcher]] locomotive. The train was still unloading passengers at the time of impact, and seven people received minor head and neck injuries. The Amtrak locomotive was attempting to couple to the train and was reportedly moving too fast.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n===2010===\nTwo significant events in 2010 received official response.\n\nOn June 21, 2010, northbound Amtrak-operated Penn Line train 538 broke down at 6:23&nbsp;p.m. Temperatures inside the train reached {{Convert|100|F|}} due to malfunctioning air conditioning. After passengers called 911, 10 people were treated at the scene for heat-related problems. All passengers were cleared from the scene by 9:40&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/22/AR2010062203752.html?wprss=rss_metro/md |title=900 riders stuck on MARC train for more than two hours with no air conditioning |last=Shaver |first=Katherine |date=June 23, 2010 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=June 30, 2010}}</ref> This incident prompted MDOT Secretary Beverley Swaim-Staley to apologize to the affected customers on June 27, 2010.\n\nOn June 28, 2010, an Amtrak engineer operating a MARC train overran a scheduled stop in {{marc|Odenton}}, without notice to passengers. Secretary Swaim-Staley was aboard the train at the time, and issued public statements about the situation. Amtrak CEO [[Joseph H. Boardman]] apologized to riders the following morning.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/29/AR2010062905054.html |title=Md. transportation secretary calls for MARC review after recent lapses |last=Dresser |first=Michael |date=June 30, 2010 |website=Washington Post |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis pair of events prompted Amtrak to draft an emergency response plan for broken down MARC trains.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/30/AR2010063005189.html |title=Amtrak unveils plan to dispatch help when MARC trains break down |last=Shaver |first=Katherine |date=July 1, 2010 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=July 7, 2010 |issn=0740-5421}}</ref>\n\n==Proposals for service expansion==\n===2007 plan===\nIn the first decade of the 21st century, MARC ridership increased significantly, and the system neared capacity for its current configuration. With the area population growing and the [[Base Realignment and Closure|BRAC]] process poised to bring new jobs to [[Aberdeen Proving Ground]] and [[Fort George G. Meade|Ft. Meade]], both near MARC stations, the state saw the need to expand service. In September 2007, MTA Maryland unveiled an ambitious 30-year plan of system improvements. Though funding sources had not been established at that time, the plan represented the state's goals of increasing capacity and flexibility. Proposed improvements included:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mtamaryland.com/marc%20plan%20full.pdf |title=MARC Growth & Investment Plan |date=September 2007 |publisher=MTA Maryland |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227000614/http://www.mtamaryland.com/marc%20plan%20full.pdf |archive-date=February 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |access-date=February 16, 2010 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n  \n*Acquisition of new equipment. 54 Bombardier MultiLevels were ordered to replace aging single-level cars.\n*Weekend service on the Penn Line. Service began on December 7, 2013, between Baltimore and Washington, D.C., with some trips extending to Martin State Airport. There are nine round trips on Saturdays (three begin and three then later end at Martin State Airport) and 6 round trips on Sundays (two begin and two then later end at Martin State Airport).<ref name=\"penn line\" />\n*Increased mid-day service and [[reverse commute]] service on the Camden and Brunswick Lines. As of 2015, there is a somewhat limited reverse commute service in effect on the [[Camden Line]].\n*Extension of service past Union Station in Washington to [[L'Enfant Plaza station|L'Enfant]] and [[Northern Virginia]] along tracks used by [[Virginia Railway Express|VRE]] trains, thus relieving pressure on the [[Washington Metro]]\n*More daily trips east of Baltimore's Penn Station, including improved service to Aberdeen Proving Ground\n*Service beyond [[Perryville station|Perryville]] to [[Newark, Delaware|Newark]] or [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]] in Delaware, providing a connection to [[SEPTA Regional Rail|SEPTA]] commuter trains to Philadelphia and beyond\n*New or expanded tunnels along the Northeast Corridor in Baltimore\n*New stations in Baltimore, providing direct connections with the [[Baltimore Metro Subway|Metro Subway]], and service to [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]] and [[Johns Hopkins Bayview Medical Center|Bayview Medical Center]]\n*Rapid transit-like service through Baltimore\n\nSome of the proposals were foreseen to take years or decades to implement, however others such as Penn Line weekend service could have begun in a matter of months, yet budgetary shortfalls prevented this. In Spring 2009, to offset such budget shortfalls, ticket sales employees at most non-Amtrak stations were replaced with Amtrak \"[[Amtrak Arrow Reservation System|Quik-Trak]]\" [[touchscreen]] ticket machines, and some train services were eliminated or scaled back. Ticket machines were also added to stations that were not previously staffed, such as {{marc|Halethorpe}}. The only remaining staffed stations, Odenton and Frederick, remained staffed by Commuter Direct.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mta-d7.cg-devel.com/news/odenton-station-now-commuter-direct-store |title=Odenton station is now a Commuter Direct Store |date=September 2009 |publisher=MTA Maryland}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.commuterpage.com/pages/tools-resources/commuter-store-commuter-direct/#store_locations |title=Commuter Direct Store Locations |date=March 2015 |publisher=Commuter Direct}}</ref>\n\n===2010s: Extension to Delaware and SEPTA===\nIn 2017, the Wilmington Area Planning Council submitted ridership studies to [[Cecil County, Maryland|Cecil County]], the [[Delaware Valley Regional Planning Commission]], [[SEPTA]] and the [[Delaware Department of Transportation]] for the extension of MARC service from [[Perryville station|Perryville]] via [[Elkton station|Elkton]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kroner |first1=Brad |title=MARC stop in Elkton moves forward, Perryville MARC facility stalls |url=https://www.cecildaily.com/spotlight/marc-stop-in-elkton-moves-forward-perryville-marc-facility-stalls/article_6fc3adeb-b5ab-5f96-890e-37862d28e2d0.html |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Cecil Whig |date=28 April 2017}}</ref> to [[Newark station (Delaware)|Newark, Delaware]], and possibly [[Wilmington station (Delaware)|Wilmington]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kroner |first1=Brad |title=Study to examine extending MARC line to Newark |url=https://www.newarkpostonline.com/news/study-to-examine-extending-marc-line-to-newark/article_f1b25144-e82b-5966-bf7d-51e9d41d52ae.html |accessdate=4 March 2019 |publisher=Newark Post (Delaware) |date=7 March 2017}}</ref> The section from Perryville to Newark is the one of only two along the [[Northeast Corridor]] not covered by commuter train service (the other is between [[New London Union Station|New London, Connecticut]], and [[Wickford Junction station|Wickford Junction, Rhode Island]]). Currently a bus, [[Cecil Transit]] Route 5, connects the two stations.<ref>{{cite book |title=Fixed Route 5 (schedule) |publisher=[[Cecil Transit]] |url=http://www.ccgov.org/home/showdocument?id=32808 |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons category|MARC Train}}\n{{Portal|Maryland|Trains}}\n*[https://mta.maryland.gov/ Maryland Transit Administration]\n*[http://mta.maryland.gov/sites/default/files/Marc_Map_and_Legend_UPDATED_2%20%282%29.JPG MARC System Map]\n*[http://www.marctracker.com/PublicView/status.html MARC Current Train Status Using GPS Technology]\n\n{{MTA Maryland}}\n{{MARC Train}}\n{{Baltimore Transit}}\n{{Transit In DC}}\n{{Northeast Corridor navbox}}\n{{USCommRail}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marc Train}}\n[[Category:MARC Train| ]]\n[[Category:Commuter rail in the United States]]\n[[Category:Railway services introduced in 1984]]\n[[Category:Maryland railroads]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C., railroads]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:Electric railways in Maryland]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Commuter rail system comprising three lines in the Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox Public transit\n|name = Maryland Area Regional Commuter Rail\n|image =MARC train.svg\n|imagesize = 260 px\n|image2 = MARC 438 (14833026066).jpg\n|imagesize2 = 310px\n|caption2 = A MARC [[Bombardier\u2013Alstom HHP-8|HHP-8]] leads an express train through {{marc|Odenton}}\n|locale = [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area]]\n|owner = [[Maryland Transit Administration]]\n|transit_type = [[Regional rail|Regional]] / [[Commuter rail|commuter]] rail\n|began_operation = {{start date and age|1984}} (as Maryland Rail Commuter)\n|chief_executive = Andrea Farmer\n|lines = 3\n|ridership = 40,100 (Q2 2016)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2016-q2-ridership-APTA.PDF |title=Transit Ridership Report Second Quarter 2016 |date=August 22, 2016 |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |via=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Pages/ridershipreport.aspx |access-date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|annual_ridership = 9,149,900 (2015)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2015-q4-ridership-APTA.pdf |title=Transit Ridership Report Fourth Quarter 2015 |date=March 2, 2016 |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |via=http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Pages/ridershipreport.aspx |access-date=July 23, 2016}}</ref>\n|operator = [[Bombardier Transportation]]<br><small>(Camden and Brunswick Lines)</small><br>[[Amtrak]]<br><small>(Penn Line)<br>(under contract to the [[Maryland Transit Administration]])</small>\n|system_length = {{cvt|187|mi}}\n|stations = 42\n|track_gauge = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}} \n|top_speed = {{cvt|125|mph}}\n|marks = MARC\n|host = [[Amtrak]]<br>[[CSX Transportation]]\n|el = [[Amtrak's 25 Hz traction power system|25Hz AC]] on the Penn Line\n|map = [[File:Marctrainmap.svg|310px|MARC oversees the Brunswick Line (orange), Camden Line (green), and Penn Line (purple).]]<br>MARC operates the Brunswick Line (orange), Camden Line (green), and Penn Line (purple).\n|map_state = collapsed\n|website = [https://mta.maryland.gov/marc-train MARC Train official page]\n|alt=|caption=|area served=|line_number=|start=|end=|character=|vehicles=\n}}\n{{MARC Train RDT}}\n\n'''MARC''' ('''Maryland Area Regional Commuter''') Train Service<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mta-d7.cg-devel.com/content/transit-information |title=Transit Information Overview |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=June 24, 2011}}</ref> {{Reporting mark|MARC}}, previously known as '''Maryland Rail Commuter''', is a [[commuter rail]] system comprising three lines in the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area]]. MARC is administered by the [[Maryland Transit Administration]] (MTA), a [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) agency, and is operated under contract by [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier Transportation Services USA Corporation]] (BTS) and [[Amtrak]] over tracks owned by [[CSX Transportation]] (CSXT) and Amtrak.\n\nWith some equipment reaching speeds of {{convert|125|mph}} on the [[Penn Line]], MARC is purported to be the fastest commuter railroad in the United States.<ref name=\"125 mph\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.metro-magazine.com/rail/article/713751/maryland-s-marc-railroad-upgrades-fleet-service-to-bolster-ridership |title=Maryland's MARC Railroad Upgrades Fleet, Service to Bolster Ridership |last=Starcic |first=Janna |date=June 17, 2016 |work=Metro Magazine |access-date=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nMARC has three lines, all of which originate and terminate at [[Washington Union Station]]. It operates 94 trains on a typical weekday: the [[Brunswick Line]] (18 trains/19 trains on Fridays),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Routes+Schedules/marc_brunswick-washington.pdf |title=MARC Brunswick Line Timetable |date=March 13, 2017 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> the [[Camden Line]] (21 trains),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Routes+Schedules/marc_camden-washington.pdf |title=MARC Camden Line Timetable |date=March 13, 2017 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Penn Line]] (58 trains).<ref name=\"penn line\">{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Routes+Schedules/marc_penn-washington.pdf |title=MARC Penn Line Full Timetable |date=March 4, 2019 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration |access-date=May 14, 2019}}</ref> The Penn Line is the only line that has weekend service, with 18 trains (comprising 9 round trips) on Saturdays, and 12 trains (comprising 6 round trips) on Sundays.<ref name=\"penn line\" /> Service is suspended or reduced on select Federal holidays.\n\nLike most commuter rail systems in North America, all MARC trains operate in [[Push-pull train|push-pull]] mode, with the [[control car|cab car]] typically leading trains traveling toward Washington. This configuration ensures that diesel locomotive fumes are kept further from the terminal at Union Station, and accommodates elevation gains by placing the locomotive at the head of trains heading outbound from Washington.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n===Brunswick Line===\n{{Main|Brunswick Line}}\nThe '''Brunswick Line''' is a {{cvt|74|mi}} line that runs on [[CSX Transportation|CSX]]-owned tracks between Washington, D.C., and [[Martinsburg station|Martinsburg, West Virginia]], with a {{cvt|14|mi}} branch to [[Frederick station|Frederick, Maryland]]. It is descended from [[Baltimore & Ohio Railroad]] (B&O) service between Washington and its northern and western suburbs.\n\n===Camden Line===\n{{Main|Camden Line}}\nThe '''Camden Line''' is a {{cvt|39|mi}} line that runs on CSX-owned tracks between Washington, D.C., and [[Camden Station]] in [[Baltimore]]. It is descended from B&O commuter routes running between Washington and Baltimore. The B&O began operating over portions of this route in 1830, making it one of the oldest passenger rail lines in the U.S. still in operation.<ref name=\"dilts\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JjrCWPwvHzIC |title=The Great Road: The Building of the Baltimore and Ohio, the Nation's First Railroad, 1828\u20131853 |last=Dilts |first=James D. |publisher=Stanford University Press |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-8047-2629-0 |location=Palo Alto, CA |page=157}}</ref>\n\n===Penn Line===\n{{Main|Penn Line}}\nThe '''Penn Line''' is a {{cvt|77|mi}} line that runs on Amtrak's [[Northeast Corridor]] tracks between Washington, D.C., and [[Perryville station|Perryville, Maryland]], via [[Pennsylvania Station (Baltimore)|Baltimore Penn Station]]. Most trains operate a {{cvt|39|mi}} stretch between Washington and Baltimore, with limited service to [[Martin State Airport station|Martin State Airport]] and Perryville. It is the fastest commuter rail line in North America, with equipment capable of operating at speeds up to {{convert|125|mph}}.<ref name=\"125 mph\" /> Descended from Washington-Baltimore commuter routes operated by the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] (hence the name), it is by far the busiest line, carrying more passengers than the other two lines combined. The Penn Line is the only line that operates on weekends.\n\n===Special Western Maryland service===\nTrains have made special weekend trips to and from [[Cumberland station (Maryland)|Cumberland, Maryland]]. Past events have included trains for [[Western Maryland]] residents to attend sporting events in the Baltimore/Washington area, such as [[Baltimore Orioles]] or [[Washington Redskins]] games, or for Baltimore/Washington residents to attend [[Railfest]] in Cumberland and enjoy the scenic mountains and fall foliage of Western Maryland.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Maryland Area Rail Commuter, A Rider's Guide |last=Stakem |first=Patrick H. |publisher=PRB Publishing |year=2008 |asin=B004U7FKQS}}</ref>\n\n===Intermodal connections===\nNearly all stations served by MARC connect with local bus or [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service. Washington Union Station, New Carrollton, College Park, Greenbelt, Silver Spring and Rockville offer connections to the [[Washington Metro|Metrorail]] subway; Baltimore Penn Station and Camden Station both offer connections to the [[Baltimore Light RailLink]]. Additionally, Washington Union Station and Baltimore Penn double as major Amtrak stations, and BWI Airport, Aberdeen, New Carrollton, Rockville, Harpers Ferry and Martinsburg are shared with Amtrak as well. Washington Union Station also offers a connection to the [[Virginia Railway Express|VRE]] network into Northern Virginia.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Point of Rocks MARC 1987.jpg|thumb|left|A MARC [[EMD F9]] leads a service through {{marc|Point of Rocks}} in 1987.]]\n\n===Origins===\nAll three MARC lines date from the 19th century. Service on the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] (B&O) between Baltimore and [[Ellicott City, Maryland|Ellicott City]] began on May 24, 1830; this route included part of what is now the Camden Line.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IEPCqQErPHAC |title=History of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad |last=Stover |first=John F. |date=January 1, 1995 |publisher=Purdue University Press |isbn=9781557530660 |language=en}}</ref> B&O service from Baltimore to Washington, the modern Camden Line route, began on August 25, 1835.<ref name=\"dilts\" />\n\nThe [[Old Main Line Subdivision|B&O's main line]] was extended to Frederick Junction (with a branch to {{marc|Frederick}}) in 1831, to {{marc|Point of Rocks}} in 1832, to {{marc|Brunswick}} and {{marc|Harpers Ferry}} in 1834, and {{marc|Martinsburg}} in 1842. The B&O completed its [[Metropolitan Subdivision|Metropolitan Branch]] in 1873; most service from Martinsburg and Frederick was diverted onto the Metropolitan Branch to Washington and the old main line became a secondary route. This established the basic route for what would become the [[Brunswick Line]].\n\nThe [[Philadelphia, Wilmington and Baltimore Railroad]] (PW&B) completed its line between Baltimore and Philadelphia in December 1838, save for the ferry across the [[Susquehanna River]], which was not bridged until the 1860s. Although the B&O was chartered with the unspoken assumption that no competing line would be built between Baltimore and Washington, the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]]-owned [[Baltimore and Potomac Railroad]] (B&P) was completed between the two cities in 1872.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mdot.maryland.gov/Office_of_Planning_and_Capital_Programming/Plans_Programs_Reports/Historical_Documents/Southern_Maryland_Commuter_Service_Technical_Memorandum_07282009.pdf |title=Southern Maryland Commuter Rail Service Feasibility Study |date=August 2009 |publisher=Maryland Transit Administration}}</ref> The PW&B was initially hostile to the Pennsylvania (PRR); however, the PRR acquired it in a stock battle with the B&O in 1881. The PW&B soon began operating PRR through service{{snd}}the ancestor of [[Penn Line]] service{{snd}}between Washington and Philadelphia in conjunction with the B&P. Meanwhile, the PRR ended B&O [[Arrangements between railroads|trackage rights]] over the PW&B in 1884, forcing it to open [[Philadelphia Subdivision|its own parallel route]] in 1886. The PW&B and the B&P were combined into the PRR's [[Philadelphia, Baltimore and Washington Railroad]] in 1902.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1902.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1902 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref>\n\nThe B&O ended local service on the [[Frederick Branch (Baltimore and Ohio Railroad)|Frederick Branch]] in November 1949. All B&O passenger service between Baltimore and Philadelphia ended in 1958; local service from Washington was curtailed to [[Camden Station]]. The B&O continued to offer local service to Brunswick plus long-distance service, while the PRR operated a mix of local, intercity, and long-distance service on the [[Northeast Corridor]]. Local service north of Baltimore on the PRR ended around 1964.\n\n===Public takeover===\n[[File:Baltimore & Ohio train 161 from the Beltway, December 1970.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad|B&O]] train near the [[Beltway]] in 1970, running on what is now the [[Camden Line]]]]\n[[File:Penn Central MP54s near Capital Beltway station, July 1970.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]] train near the Beltway in 1970, running on what is now the [[Penn Line]]]]\nIn the mid-20th century, passenger rail service declined owing to a variety of factors{{snd}}particularly the advent of the automobile{{snd}}even while commuting between suburban locations and urban business districts remained common. In 1968, the PRR folded into [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]], which took over its passenger operations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1968.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1968 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> On May 1, 1971, [[Amtrak]] took over most intercity passenger service in the United States, including some trains on the B&O and PRR.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.timetables.org/full.php?group=19710501&item=0008 |title=Nationwide Schedules of Intercity Passenger Service |date=May 1, 1971 |publisher=National Railroad Passenger Corporation (Amtrak) |page=6 |via=The Museum of Railway Timetables}}</ref> The remaining Washington\u2013Baltimore and Washington\u2013Brunswick commuter service was operated by the B&O and Penn Central without subsidies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1971.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1971 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref>\n\nAmtrak initially operated (with federal subsidy) the Washington\u2013[[Parkersburg, West Virginia|Parkersburg]] ''[[West Virginian (Amtrak train)|West Virginian]]'' (later renamed ''Potomac Turbo'' then ''Potomac Special'') The ''Potomac Special'' was cut back to a {{convert|146|mile|adj=on}} commuter-based Washington\u2013Cumberland trip, the ''[[Blue Ridge (train)|Blue Ridge]]'', on May 7, 1973. In early 1974, the B&O threatened to discontinue its remaining unsubsidized commuter services, citing heavy losses. On March 1, 1974, the [[Maryland Department of Transportation]] (MDOT) began a 50% subsidy of the B&O's Washington\u2013Brunswick and Washington\u2013Baltimore service{{snd}}the first state-sponsored commuter rail service to Washington.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1974.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1974 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref><ref name=\"marchistory\">{{Cite web |url=http://mtamaryland.com/about/transitprofiles/MARC_History.cfm |title=History of MARC Train |publisher=Maryland Department of Transportation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117174532/http://mtamaryland.com/about/transitprofiles/MARC_History.cfm |archive-date=January 17, 2010}}</ref> In 1975, the state signed an operating agreement with the B&O, under which the state provided rolling stock and reimbursed the railroad for all operating losses.<ref name=\"marchistory\" /> On October 31, 1976, Amtrak introduced the Washington\u2013Cincinnati ''[[Shenandoah (Amtrak train)|Shenandoah]]'' and cut the ''Blue Ridge'' to a {{convert|73|mile|adj=on}} Washington\u2013Martinsburg trip.<ref name=intercity>{{cite web |title=West Virginia State Rail Plan: Intercity Service Review |author=West Virginia Department of Transportation, State Rail Authority |date=March 12, 2013  |url=http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Intercity_Service_Review.sflb.ashx |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006131524/http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Intercity_Service_Review.sflb.ashx |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |pages=4\u20136}}</ref> In the late 1970s, West Virginia began to fund the B&O shuttles between Brunswick and Martinsburg; the shuttles were soon incorporated as extensions of Brunswick service in order to secure [[Federal Transit Administration|Urban Mass Transportation Administration]] subsidies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Maryland_Area_Regional_Commuter_Service.sflb.ashx |title=West Virginia State Rail Plan: Maryland Area Regional Commuter Service |date=March 12, 2013 |publisher=West Virginia Department of Transportation, State Rail Authority |access-date=October 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006071936/http://www.westvirginiarailplan.com/Libraries/project_information/WV_SRP_-_Maryland_Area_Regional_Commuter_Service.sflb.ashx |archive-date=October 6, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In December 1981, MDOT purchased 22 ex-PRR coaches for use on B&O lines.<ref name=\"baer1980\" /> The Maryland State Railroad Administration (SRA) was established in 1986 to administer contracts, procure rolling stock, and oversee short line railroads in the state.<ref name=\"marchistory\" />\n\n[[Conrail]] took over the unsubsidized ex-PRR Baltimore\u2013Washington service from Penn Central at its creation on April 1, 1976.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1976.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1976 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> MDOT began subsidizing that service after Conrail threatened to discontinue service on April 1, 1977.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1977.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1977 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> Prior to 1978, most ex-PRR Baltimore\u2013Washington service was operated by aging [[PRR MP54|MP54]] [[electric multiple unit]]s, most dating back to the line's 1933 electrification. In 1978, Amtrak and the City of Baltimore negotiated with the [[New Jersey Department of Transportation]] to lease a number of new [[Arrow (railcar)|Arrow]] railcars to replace the MP54s.<ref name=\"baer1978\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1977.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1977 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> With funding from Pennsylvania and Maryland, Amtrak used some of the cars to initiate a Philadelphia\u2013Washington commuter trip, the ''[[Chesapeake (train)|Chesapeake]]'', on April 30, 1978.<ref name=\"baer1978\" /> The ''Chesapeake'' stopped at some local stations but fewer than the Conrail service; it provided commuter service from north of Baltimore for the first time since the 1960s.\n\n[[BWI Rail Station]] opened for Amtrak and Conrail trains on October 26, 1980.<ref>{{Cite news |title=BWI Airport Rail Link Celebrates Opening |last=Shifrin |first=Carole |date=October 24, 1980 |work=The Washington Post |page=D3 |id = {{ProQuest|147198286}}}}</ref> In August 1982, Conrail trains began stopping at [[Capital Beltway station]], used by intercity trains since 1970. {{marc|Lanham}} and {{marc|Landover}} stations were closed.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Commuter Trains' New Stop: Beltway Station |date=August 11, 1982 |work=The Washington Post |page=MD11 |id = {{ProQuest|147456718}}}}</ref> Two additional round trips{{snd}}one in the peak direction, and one reverse for commuters working in Baltimore{{snd}}were added on July 5, 1983.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Baltimore-D.C. Commuter Train Trips to Increase |last=Lynton |first=Stephen J. |date=June 9, 1983 |work=The Washington Post |page=B8 |id = {{ProQuest|147548056}}}}</ref> On October 30, 1983, Amtrak and MARC moved from Capital Beltway into a new platform and waiting room at nearby [[New Carrollton station]], served by Metro since 1978.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Fuchs |first=Tom |date=April 2009 |title=30th Anniversary of New Carrollton Station |url=http://www.actfortransit.org/archives/publications/TransitTimes-V23-2-Apr2009.pdf |journal=Transit Times |volume=23 |issue=2 |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Metro Parking Spots Rented to Amtrak For Temporary Use at New Carrollton |date=October 28, 1983 |work=The Washington Post |page=C12 |id = {{ProQuest|147479061}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://history.amtrak.com/archives/i-new-i-new-carrollton-station-brochure-1983 |title=New New Carrollton station |date=1983 |publisher=Amtrak}}</ref> The [[West Baltimore station#History|Edmondson Avenue]] and Frederick Road stops in Baltimore were replaced by [[West Baltimore station]] on April 30, 1984.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18762237/marc_west_baltimore/ |title=New station, schedule for rail users |last=McCord |first=Joel |date=April 28, 1984 |work=Baltimore Sun |via=Newspapers.com}}{{free access}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, MDOT began installing highway signs to point drivers to commuter rail stations.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bulletin Board |date=May 28, 1981 |work=The Washington Post |page=MD9 |id = {{ProQuest|147307755}}}}</ref> In 1982, law changes allowed Conrail to shed its commuter rail operations in order to focus on its more profitable freight operations. On January 1, 1983, public operators (including [[Metro-North Railroad]], [[NJ Transit]], and [[SEPTA Regional Rail]]) took over Conrail commuter rail systems in the Northeast. MDOT began paying Amtrak to run the ex-PRR Washington\u2013Baltimore service.<ref name=\"marchistory\" /><ref name=\"baer1980\" /> That service was branded as AMDOT (Amtrak Maryland Department of Transportation).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1983/07/11/many-commute-from-baltimore-to-district-jobs/3842d475-8495-411f-af33-6d7a2be73453/ |title=Many Commute From Baltimore To District Jobs |last=Sargent |first=Edward D. |date=July 11, 1983 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> On October 1983, with low patronage and largely duplicated by the MDOT-subsidized service, the ''Chesapeake'' was discontinued. In 1984, the SRA renamed its three subsidized lines as ''MARC'' as a branding strategy. Operations remained the same, but public-facing elements like schedules and crew uniforms were consolidated under the new name.<ref name=\"marchistory\" /><ref name=\"baer1980\" /> MARC soon began calling its three lines the [[Penn Line]], [[Camden Line]], and [[Brunswick Line]].\n\n===Improved service===\n[[File:MARC 64 Jessup MD June 94 - Flickr - drewj1946.jpg|thumb|right|MARC train led by an [[EMD E9]] (former [[Burlington Northern]]) at Jessup in 1994]]\nIn October 1986, MARC began testing an Amtrak [[EMD AEM-7|AEM-7]] locomotive, looking to use push-pull trains to replace the Arrows.<ref name=\"baer1980\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.prrths.com/newprr_files/Hagley/PRR1980.pdf |title=A GENERAL CHRONOLOGY OF THE SUCCESSORS OF THE PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD COMPANY AND THEIR HISTORICAL CONTEXT: 1980\u201389 |last=Baer |first=Christopher T. |date=April 2015 |publisher=Pennsylvania Railroad Technical and Historical Society}}</ref> On February 27, 1989, MARC increased Washington\u2013Baltimore service from 7 to 13 weekday round trips. A new park-and-ride station opened at {{marc|Bowie State}} (site of Jericho Park station, closed in 1981) and [[Bowie Railroad Buildings|Bowie station]] was closed.<ref name=\"baer1980\" /> Two more round trips were added in May 1989.<ref name=\"baer1980\" />\n\nOn May 1, 1991, MARC service was extended north from Baltimore to {{marc|Perryville}} with intermediate stops at {{marc|Martin State Airport}}, {{marc|Edgewood}}, and {{marc|Aberdeen}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1991-05-01/news/1991121140_1_perryville-commuter-rail-service-marc |title=Commuter rail, Perryville to Baltimore, starts today: MARC line's new Susquehanna Flyer out to attract commuters. ALL ABOARD! |last=Reid |first=Bruce |date=May 1, 1991 |work=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> Between 1988 and 1993, MARC expanded service from 34 to 70 total daily trips across the system.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1993-07-24/news/1993205036_1_buckley-marc-system-camden-station |title=MARC plans to raise fares 19 percent boost to be proposed |last=Lee |first=Edward |date=July 24, 1993 |work=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> In 1995, 800 parking spaces were added to [[Odenton station]].<ref name=\"parking1995\" />\n\nFrom 1989 to 1996, the Camden Line had high ridership growth and substantial changes to its stations. A new station at {{marc|Savage}} just off [[Maryland Route 32|Route 32]] was opened on July 31, 1989.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Columbia Commuters Get a Station Break: Convenience Touted at New MARC Stop in Savage Station Opens in Savage |last=Worden |first=Amy |date=August 3, 1989 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|139977789}}}}</ref> MARC began service to [[Greenbelt station]] in May 1993, seven months before Metro began serving the station.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1993/12/10/lukewarm-thrill-at-end-of-line/017c98b2-5d12-4e61-ad31-2e89e54109e6/ |title=LUKEWARM THRILL AT END OF LINE |last=Meyer |first=Eugene L. |date=December 10, 1993 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On January 31, 1994, MARC expanded midday service on the Camden and Brunswick lines, opened [[Laurel Race Track station]] to relieve a parking shortage at [[Laurel station (MARC)|Laurel station]], and closed the underused Berwyn station on the Camden Line.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-01-18/news/1994018046_1_marc-midday-service-union-station |title=MARC is off to the races Jan. 31 |last=Jensen |first=Peter |date=January 18, 1994 |newspaper=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> On December 12, 1994, [[Muirkirk station (MARC)|Muirkirk station]] (originally planned as South Laurel) was opened to reduce congestion on nearby [[U.S. Route 1 in Maryland|Route 1]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Commuter Lines Add Stations in Va. and Md. |last=Fehr |first=Stephen |date=December 12, 1994 |work=The Washington Post |page=D3 |id = {{ProQuest|757194485}}}}</ref> In 1996, a $1.2 million project added 600 parking spaces at Savage station to relieve crowding.<ref name=\"parking1995\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1995-06-22/news/1995173023_1_commuters-marc-stations-parking-lots |title=600 spaces to be added to MARC station parking lot by spring |last=Hedgpeth |first=Dana |date=June 22, 1995 |work=The Baltimore Sun}}</ref> In July 1996, the Elkridge station was closed and replaced with [[Dorsey station]], which has a larger parking area and a dedicated interchange with [[Maryland Route 100|Route 100]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-56834962.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911025205/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-56834962.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 11, 2016 |title=State DOT Considers New Road near Dulles |last=Spellmann |first=Karyn |date=July 8, 1996 |work=The Washington Times |url-access=subscription  |via=Highbeam Research}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baltometro.org/reports/MajorTransMilestones.pdf |title=MAJOR TRANSPORTATION MILESTONES IN THE BALTIMORE REGION SINCE 1940 |last=Logan |first=Mary |date=December 1, 2005 |publisher=Baltimore Metropolitan Council |page=12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227234104/http://www.baltometro.org/reports/MajorTransMilestones.pdf |archive-date=December 27, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 1987, the B&O was merged into [[CSX Transportation|CSX]]. CSX continued to operate Camden and Brunswick Line service.<ref name=\"baer1980\" /> On July 6, 1987, MARC opened [[Metropolitan Grove station]] \u2013 the first new station on the Brunswick line in over a century.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=Summer 1987 |title=News and Upcoming Events |url=http://actfortransit.org/archives/publications/TransitTimes-V01-2-Sum1987.pdf |journal=Transit Times |publisher=Action Committee for Transit |volume=1 |issue=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Md. Commuters Get Another Way to Go |date=July 9, 1987 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|139235759}}}}</ref>\n\n===Keolis controversy===\nBeginning as early as June 2010, MARC began looking for a new operator to replace [[CSX Transportation]] for the [[Camden Line|Camden]] and [[Brunswick Line|Brunswick]] Lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trn.trains.com/news/news-wire/2010/06/marc-to-seek-new-operator-for-csx-run-routes|title=MARC to seek new operator for CSX-run routes|publisher=Trains Magazine|date=14 June 2010|accessdate=14 June 2010 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nControversy first arose when the French-owned and [[Montgomery County, Maryland]]-based [[Keolis]] (already operating [[Virginia Railway Express]] trains) was the only bidder for the contract. The bidding process was suspended in the fall of 2010 due to lack of competition. Before bidding reopened in 2011, Maryland passed a law (at the request of Leo Bretholz and other [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivors) requiring Keolis's majority owner, French state railway company [[SNCF]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/07/06/AR2010070605169_2.html?sid=ST2010070605786 |title=Holocaust group faults VRE contract |last=Shaver |first=Katherine |date=July 7, 2010 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref> to fully disclose its role in transporting Jews to concentration camps during [[World War II]] (while SNCF was under control of the Nazi government). This disclosure would need to meet the satisfaction of the Maryland state archivist before Keolis would be allowed to place a bid for MARC service. Keolis faced similar issues while bidding for VRE operations in 2009, but was eventually given that contract.\n\nKeolis and SNCF lawyers claimed that all documentation required by the law had been produced long before.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wbaltv.com/politics/27069604/detail.html |title=No way to run a railroad |date=March 3, 2011 |publisher=WBAL TV |access-date=September 1, 2012}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This was also asserted by Don Phillips in the July 2011 issue of ''[[Trains (magazine)|Trains Magazine]]''. Phillips states that a full 914-page independent report and complete history of SNCF's role in the Holocaust, released in 1996, is currently being translated into English.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Phillips |first=Don |date=July 2011 |title=Lawsuits, Commuter Trains and the Holocaust |magazine=[[Trains (magazine)|Trains]] |page=11}}</ref> Phillips cites from the publicly available English introduction to the report, noting that while some SNCF workers worked with the Nazis, acts of sabotage were frequent, and the Nazis shot 819 SNCF workers for refusing to carry out the rail orders of the government. An additional 1200 railway workers were themselves sent to concentration camps over SNCF rails. Phillips also notes that SNCF does business with the [[Israel Railways|Israel rail system]] and works without government prompting to educate the current generation about the war and Holocaust.\n\nIn June 2011, the future of Keolis's ability to bid on the MARC contract remained up in the air with the new disclosure law in place. No other bidder had emerged to replace CSXT. On June 5, 2011, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' ran an editorial critical of the disclosure law. The Post claimed that SNCF has been working for years on digitizing its records, and the Maryland law may require items or formats counter to SNCF's current system and/or French law. The article also stated that some in the Maryland Attorney General's Office worried the law was not Constitutional, may risk retaliation towards Maryland firms overseas, and may risk federal funding for Maryland \"by imposing arbitrary procurement demands on a single company.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/no-way-to-run-a-railroad/2011/06/03/AGk2gmJH_story.html |title=No way to run a railroad |last=Lind |first=Michael |date=June 5, 2011 |work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.jewishtimes.com/index.php/jewishtimes/news/jt/local_news/state_archivist_sncf_archives_might_not_be_enough/29884 |title=State archivist SNCF archives might not be enough |last=Rubin |first=Neil |date=February 10, 2012 |work=Baltimore Jewish Times}}</ref>\n\nMTA issued a new Request for Proposals for the operations and maintenance of MARC services on the Brunswick and Camden Lines on July 14, 2011, with a deadline for proposals on November 21, 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.masstransitmag.com/news/10454236/md-mta-keolis-mum-on-bids-to-run-marc-lines |title=MD MTA Keolis mum on bids to run MARC lines |last=Sohr |first=Nicholas |date=November 21, 2011 |work=The Daily Record via masstransitmag.com}}</ref> On October 17, 2012, a $204 million contract to run the Camden and Brunswick lines was awarded to the [[Canada|Canadian]] company [[Bombardier Transportation]],<ref name=\"Weir\">{{Cite news |url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/bombardier-wins-204m-marc-commuter-train-contract/article/2511058#.UI1WIWe_Msc |title=Bombardier wins $204m MARC commuter train contract |last=Weir |first=Kytja |date=October 17, 2012 |work=[[The Washington Examiner]] |access-date=October 28, 2012}}</ref> effectively ending the Keolis controversy. The pre-service transition period began on the Thursday of that week, during which time CSXT continued to operate MARC trains.<ref name=\"Weir\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/dr-gridlock/wp/2012/10/17/new-company-to-operate-some-marc-trains/ |title=New company to operate some MARC trains |last=Shaver |first=Katherine |date=October 17, 2012 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=December 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Rolling stock==\n{{As of|2018}}, MARC operates with the following equipment:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedieselshop.us/MARC.HTML|title=Maryland Rail Commuter Roster|website=www.thedieselshop.us|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Locomotives ===\n====Current====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Image || Manufacturer || Model || Quantity || Unit Numbers || Notes\n|-\n| [[File:MARC GP39PH-2 70.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD GP40-based passenger locomotives#GP39H-2|GP39H-2]] || 6 || 70\u201375 || Entered service in 1992.\n|-\n| [[File:MARC 4911 (14669332360).jpg|150px]]\n| [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier\u2013]] [[Alstom]] || [[Bombardier\u2013Alstom HHP-8|HHP-8]] || 6 || 4910\u20134915 ||\nOnly electric locomotives in fleet, first entered service in 1998. All units underwent refurbishment in 2017\u20132018.<ref name=\"marc-advisory-council-september-2017\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.mta.maryland.gov/ckfinder/userfiles/files/MARCRAC_Minutes_2017-09-21.pdf |title=MARC Riders Advisory Council Meeting Minutes |date=September 21, 2017 |website=MTA Maryland |accessdate=June 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:MARC 29 (9116980755).jpg|150px]]\n| [[MPI MPXpress|MPI]] || [[MPI MPXpress#MP36PH-3C|MP36PH-3C]] || 26 || 10\u201335 ||\nReplaced GP40WH-2s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtamaryland.com/services/marc/serviceInformation/On_Your_MARC_Text.cfm |title=MTA Expands MARC Penn Line Service |publisher=MTA Maryland Service Information |accessdate=February 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331152834/http://www.mtamaryland.com/services/marc/serviceInformation/On_Your_MARC_Text.cfm |archivedate=March 31, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Entered service December 2009.\n|-\n|[[File:MARC Charger Testing in Odenton.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Siemens]] || [[Siemens Charger|SC-44]] || 8<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Board Of Public Works Approves $58 Million Contract For Eight MARC Locomotives |date=September 17, 2015 |publisher=[[Maryland Transit Administration]] |location=Baltimore, Maryland |url=http://mta.maryland.gov/board-public-works-approves-58-million-contract-eight-marc-locomotives |access-date=January 23, 2018}}</ref> || 80\u201387 ||Delivered December 2017 \u2013 April 2018<ref name=\"jan 2018 minutes\">{{Cite web |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/mta-website-staging/mta-website-staging/files/Community/MARCRAC_Minutes_20178-01-18.pdf |title=MARC Riders Advisory Council Meeting Summary Minutes |website=MTA Maryland |date=January 18, 2018 |access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mta.maryland.gov/content/penn-line-schedule-change-april-23 |title=Penn Line schedule change: April 23 |website=MTA Maryland |access-date=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n====Former====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Image || Manufacturer || Model || Quantity || Unit Numbers || Notes\n|-\n| [[File:EMD AEM-7 MARC 4902 at Union Station.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]]/[[ASEA]] || [[EMD AEM-7|AEM-7]] || 4 || 4900\u20134903 ||\nRetired as of April 2017, units were placed in storage,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mta-d7.cg-devel.com/sites/default/files/MARCRAC_Minutes_2017-04-20.pdf |title=MARC Riders Advisory Council Meeting Minutes |date=April 20, 2017 |website=MTA Maryland |access-date=June 2, 2019}}</ref> pending disposition.\n|-\n| [[File:MARC52.jpg|150px]]\n| [[Electro-Motive Diesel|EMD]] || [[EMD GP40-based passenger locomotives#GP40WH-2|GP40WH-2]] || 19 || 51\u201369 || \nReplaced by MP36PH-3Cs. Units 67\u201369 were rebuilt from [[EMD GP40|GP40]] work locomotives 30\u201332. One unit, no. 68, remains for non-revenue work